 #emptydefaultexceptionhandler
 
 
Empty Default Exception Handler

 Poor Error Handling: Empty Default Exception Handler. Ignoring an exception can cause the program to overlook unexpected states and conditions.
 

 
 

 
 #web.xmlerror-code
 
 
Error-code setting

 The setting defines HTTP status code that make a receiver to redirect users to a certain URL. So, the setting configures error pages for different HTTP status codes. The recommended range of values if 400-414, 500, 502-504.
 

 
 

 
 #96
 
 
Hardcoded Password

 Hardcoded or empty passwords could lead to system compromising that is hard to eliminate.
 

 
 

 
 #web.xmlhttp-only
 
 
Http-only setting

 The setting defines httpOnly flag for Set-Cookie HTTP header that restricts Cookie data reading/writing via JavaScript.
 

 
 

 
 #dc-fp-cve-2015-9251dc-fp-cve-2019-11358dc-fp-cve-2020-11023dc-fp-cve-2020-110222.0.1
 
 
jquery 2.0.1

 
  •  jQuery before 3.0.0 is vulnerable to Cross-site Scripting (XSS) attacks when a cross-domain Ajax request is performed without the dataType option, causing text/javascript responses to be executed. - 


    
        


    
    
        
    
            
    jQuery before 3.0.0 is vulnerable to Cross-site Scripting (XSS) attacks when a cross-domain Ajax request is performed without the dataType option, causing text/javascript responses to be executed.
    

    
    


    • 

  •  jQuery before 3.4.0, as used in Drupal, Backdrop CMS, and other products, mishandles jQuery.extend(true, {}, ...) because of Object.prototype pollution. If an unsanitized source object contained an enumerable __proto__ property, it could extend the native Object.prototype. - 


    
        


    
    
        
    
            
    jQuery before 3.4.0, as used in Drupal, Backdrop CMS, and other products, mishandles jQuery.extend(true, {}, ...) because of Object.prototype pollution. If an unsanitized source object contained an enumerable __proto__ property, it could extend the native Object.prototype.
    

    
    


    •

    • 

  •  In jQuery versions greater than or equal to 1.2 and before 3.5.0, passing HTML from untrusted sources - even after sanitizing it - to one of jQuery's DOM manipulation methods (i.e. .html(), .append(), and others) may execute untrusted code. This problem is patched in jQuery 3.5.0. - 


    
        


    
    
        
    
            
    In jQuery versions greater than or equal to 1.2 and before 3.5.0, passing HTML from untrusted sources - even after sanitizing it - to one of jQuery's DOM manipulation methods (i.e. .html(), .append(), and others) may execute untrusted code. This problem is patched in jQuery 3.5.0.
    

    
    



 

 
 

 
 #jqueryhtmlinsidedom
 
 
JQuery HTML Inside DOM

 Selector vulnerability, adding HTML code in page's DOM structure.
 

 
 

 
 #jqueryunsafefunctionsfordom
 
 
JQuery Unsafe functions for DOM

 Unsafe functions add HTML code for DOM structure.
 

 
 

 
 #jquerywrapelementtohtml
 
 
JQuery Wrap Element to HTML

 Wrap element to HTML code.
 

 
 

 
 #logforging
 
 
Log Forging

 

                
An application does not sufficiently validate user input that allows an attacker to create a malformed log file or inject an arbitrary code.


                
A web application can generate log file entities based on user input data. Because of insufficient data processing, an attacker can inject dividing characters and therefore create a malformed log file entity, making it impossible to automatically process this file. Also, an attacker can inject malware and use it for further attacks.

			   
                
Please fins the vulnerable script example below:

			   
                
                
$result = $authService->authenticate($login, $password);

if (!$result->isValid()) {
    $log->write("Authentication failed for user '$login'");
}

                
            


            


            

                
Recommendations

                
We recommend you process log file data to delete or escape formaztting characters.

            


            

                
Links

                
                    
                    
  • 
                        Log Forging https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Log_Forging
                    
    • 
                

                
    
                    
  • 
                        CWE-117: Improper Output Neutralization for Logs  http://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/117.html
                    
    • 
                

            

 

 
 

 
 #remotecodeexecution
 
 
Remote Code Execution

 

            
A web application can generate executable code base on user input. An attacker can execute arbitrary code if there is no processing of special characters that can modify syntax or code behavior.

            
A vulnerable script example:

            
                
if (isset($_GET['documents'])) {
    $documents = eval('return array(' . $_GET['documents'] . ');');
    foreach ($documents as $document) {
        // Processing document ...
    }
}
                
            

            
In this example, an attacker sends a malware code to a script, and the application executes this code. The figure shows an attack example via phpinfo function:

            

                
Figure 1. Arbitrary Code Execution attack

            
 

            
Recommendations

            
To eliminate the vulnerability, conduct application refactoring to ensure it does not include sections that dynamically generate executable code. We also recommend executing application code in isolated environment.

        


        

            
Links

            
                    
                
  • Code Injection https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Code_Injection
    • 
                
  • CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection') http://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html
    • 
            

        

 

 
 

 
 #web.xmlsecure
 
 
Secure setting in web.xml

 The setting defines secure flag for Set-Cookie HTTP header that defines if cookie are sent via secure connections only (https).
 

 
 

 
 #serversideinjectionsetinterval
 
 
Server Side Injection - setInterval()

 User controlled data in 'setInterval()' can result in Server Side Injection (SSI) or Remote Code Execution (RCE).
 

 
 

 
 #serversideinjectionsettimeout
 
 
Server Side Injection - setTimeout()

 User controlled data in 'setTimeout()' can result in Server Side Injection (SSI) or Remote Code Execution (RCE).
 

 
 

 
 #web.xmlsession-timeout
 
 
Session-timeout setting

 The setting defines session lifetime in minutes.
 

 
 

 
 #web.xmltracking-mode
 
 
Tracking-mode setting

 The setting defines if a session ID (JSESSIONID) is sent as a URL parameter or is stored in user Cookie.
 

 
 

 
 #web.xmltransport-guarantee
 
 
Transport-guarantee setting

 The setting defines if encrypted SSL connections are used for data transferring.
